## Overview
Splunk is one of the most widely used SIEM platforms. It collects machine and
network logs, normalises them, and makes them searchable in real time so
analysts can spot and investigate activity quickly. This room was my first
hands-on look at how Splunk is built and how data moves through it.

## How Splunk is structured
Splunk has three core components that work together to turn raw logs into
something searchable:

**Forwarder** — a lightweight agent on the machine you want to monitor. It
collects data and ships it to Splunk with minimal impact on the host. Typical
sources: web servers, Windows hosts (Event Logs, PowerShell, Sysmon), Linux
hosts, and databases.

**Indexer** — receives data from forwarders, parses and normalises it into
field-value pairs, categorises it, and stores it as events. This is the step
that makes the data searchable.

**Search Head** — where you query the indexed data, inside the Search &
Reporting app, using SPL (Search Processing Language). It also turns results
into tables and visualisations like bar and pie charts.

So the flow is: **source → Forwarder → Indexer → Search Head.**

